<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a regular expression?", answer: "A regular expression (regex) is a pattern that describes a set of strings. It is used for searching, matching, and manipulating text. For example, the pattern \\d+ matches one or more digits, [a-z]+ matches one or more lowercase letters, and .* matches any character sequence. Regular expressions are supported in virtually every programming language." },
  { question: "What are regex flags?", answer: "Flags modify how a regex pattern is applied. The global flag (g) finds all matches instead of just the first. The case-insensitive flag (i) matches regardless of letter case. The multiline flag (m) makes ^ and $ match the start and end of each line rather than the entire string. Flags can be combined for more flexible matching." },
  { question: "What are capture groups?", answer: "Capture groups are portions of a regex pattern enclosed in parentheses. They capture the matched text for later use. For example, (\\w+)@(\\w+) applied to 'user@host' captures 'user' as group 1 and 'host' as group 2. Capture groups are essential for extracting specific parts of matched text." },
  { question: "Why is my regex not matching?", answer: "Common reasons include: forgetting to escape special characters (use \\. to match a literal period), not enabling the global flag to find all matches, not enabling case-insensitive mode, incorrect character classes, or quantifier issues. Check that your pattern matches the exact text format and try testing with simpler patterns first." },
  { question: "What is the difference between * and + quantifiers?", answer: "The * quantifier matches zero or more occurrences, while + matches one or more. For example, \\d* matches an empty string or any number of digits, but \\d+ requires at least one digit. Use * when the element is optional and + when at least one occurrence is required. The ? quantifier matches zero or one occurrence." }
]) %>

